    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking 'What is this?' (Masculine and Feminine)"
        },
        "text": "To ask 'What is this?' in Levantine Arabic, we use different forms depending on whether the object is masculine or feminine. 'شو' (shoo) means 'what'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "شو هاد؟",
            "english": "What is this? (masculine)",
            "transliteration": "Shoo haad?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "شو هادي؟",
            "english": "What is this? (feminine)",
            "transliteration": "Shoo haadi?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Common Masculine Personal Objects"
        },
        "text": "Here are some common personal objects that are grammatically masculine in Arabic. We use 'هاد' (haad) for 'this' when referring to them.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "موبايل",
            "english": "Mobile phone",
            "transliteration": "Mobayl"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "كتاب",
            "english": "Book",
            "transliteration": "Ktaab"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "قَلَم",
            "english": "Pen",
            "transliteration": "Qalam"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Common Feminine Personal Objects"
        },
        "text": "Here are some common personal objects that are grammatically feminine in Arabic. We use 'هادي' (haadi) for 'this' when referring to them. Feminine nouns often end with a 'ة' (ta marbuta).",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "شنطة",
            "english": "Bag",
            "transliteration": "Shanṭa"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "ساعة",
            "english": "Watch/Clock",
            "transliteration": "Saa'a"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "ورقة",
            "english": "Paper (sheet)",
            "transliteration": "Wara'a"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
