    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking 'Whose is this?' (Masculine and Feminine)"
        },
        "text": "To ask 'Whose is this?' in Levantine Arabic, we use 'لمين' (lameen) which means 'whose' or 'to whom'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "لمين هاد الموبايل؟",
            "english": "Whose mobile phone is this? (masculine)",
            "transliteration": "Lameen haad il-mobayl?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "لمين هادي الشنطة؟",
            "english": "Whose bag is this? (feminine)",
            "transliteration": "Lameen haadi ish-shanṭa?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Saying 'It's mine' or 'It's yours'"
        },
        "text": "We can specify possession using 'إلـ' (il-) followed by a suffix. This indicates 'belonging to'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "إلي",
            "english": "Mine",
            "transliteration": "Illi"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "إلكَ",
            "english": "Yours (masculine singular)",
            "transliteration": "Illak"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "إلكِ",
            "english": "Yours (feminine singular)",
            "transliteration": "Illik"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Using Possessive Suffixes with Nouns"
        },
        "text": "You can also attach possessive suffixes directly to nouns to indicate ownership, similar to 'my', 'your', 'his', 'her'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "كتابي",
            "english": "My book",
            "transliteration": "Ktaabi"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "موبايلَك",
            "english": "Your (masculine) mobile phone",
            "transliteration": "Mobaylak"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "شنطتِك",
            "english": "Your (feminine) bag",
            "transliteration": "Shanṭtik"
          }
        ]
      }
